#Memory Management
my_x = [100, 200, 300, 400]
my_y = (200, 300, 400, 500)

#Lists (my_x):

#Lists are mutable, which means we can change the values after creating them.

#Each element of the list is stored at its own memory address.

#If we change one element, Python gives that element a new memory address, but the other elements usually stay the same.

#Example: If we do my_x[0] = 999, only the first element’s address changes.

#Tuples (my_y):

#Tuples are immutable, so once we create them, we cannot change any element.

#Python often keeps the same memory address for each element in the tuple because nothing will change.

#This makes tuples slightly more efficient in memory than lists.

